Date: 0/0/1973
Source: NZ Alpine Plants
Author: MARK & ADAMS
Vol / Page: 10
Edition:
Quote: Usually it is silver beech <i>Nothofagus  menziesii</i> with small toothed leaves but in the drier areas, especially Canterbury, eastern Nelson and Marlborough in the South Island and on the highly porous soils of the volcanic plateau in the North Island, silver beech is replaced by mountain beech with small, smoothed-edged leaves.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1978
Source: Oxford Book of NZ Plants
Author: MOORE & IRWIN
Vol / Page: 80
Edition:
Quote: <i>NOTHOFAGUS MENZIESII, silver beech</i>. A hardy tree, growing from sea level to timber line and often forming pure forests, especially in Nelson and Southland. ...Some stems become malformed through infestations of mistletoe, <i>Elytranthe colensoi</i>, and it is the only known host for our three species of <i>Cyttaria,</i> strawberry fungi which cause large galls.
Notes:

